clock

Class SortedArrayPriorityQueue<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • clock.SortedArrayPriorityQueue<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of things being stored. Testing branch
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    PriorityQueue<T>

    public class SortedArrayPriorityQueue<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements PriorityQueue<T>
    Implementation of the PriorityQueue ADT using a sorted array for storage. Because Java does not allow generic arrays (!), this is implemented as an array of Object rather than of PriorityItem<T>, which would be natural. Array elements accessed then have to be cast to PriorityItem<T> before using their getItem() or getPriority() methods. This is an example of Java's poor implementation getting in the way. Java fanboys will no doubt explain at length why it has to be this way, but note that Eiffel allows it because Eiffel generics were done right from the start, rather than being tacked on as an afterthought and limited by issues of backward compatibility. Humph!
